\begin{frame}{Example 7: Homework}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Solve Exercise 2.13  from Tadelis, "Game Theory", Page 40.
        \item In addition, solve part (a)  for the case when $u(x)=x.$ Is your answer different from the logarithmic utility case?
       \item Solve part (b)  for the case when $u(x)=x.$ Is your answer different from the logarithmic utility case?
    \end{itemize}
    
    \textbf{Hint: } To solve the question, you need to set up the Lagrangian:

\[L=ln(x_1)+\delta \ln(x_2)+\delta^2  \ln(x_3)-\lambda [x_1+x_2+x_3-100]\]

FOC: with respect to $x_1$: 

FOC: with respect to $x_2$:

FOC: with respect to $x_3$:

Solve this to get rid of $\lambda$, and you are done with the first part.

The case of $u(x)=x$ is tricky, use the fact that $\delta=0.9<1$.
\end{frame}
